.chap(Introduction,intro)
.sec(Abstract,abstract)

PPL (the Polymorphic Programming Language) is a conversational, extensible language
oriented toward personal rather than institutional uses
of computers. For example, in PPL one can
write a program in twenty minutes
to differentiate formulas, but a PPL program to do large reactor
core calculations or to compute payrolls,
although possible, would be quite impractical.
PPL has been designed to promote rapid
composition, modification and debugging of programs over a
wide variety of application areas.  To achieve this property,
the mechanical efficiency of the language has been consciously
sacrificed, in certain cases, in favor of flexibility and generality.

PPL is a typeless
conversational language similar to @@<Iverson,K.E.>'s <<APL>
in which the Iversonian mechanics of arrays have been subtracted
out, and to which powerful data definition
and operator definition facilities have been added.
The syntax has been augmented to include
convenient forms for performing iterations and conditional
operations, and to allow the use of functions taking
any number of arguments.

PPL's conversational mechanics include the abilities to
trace running programs, to interrupt running programs, to set
and remove breakpoints, to write programs that converse with users, and to
edit the text of programs.  Running time is proportional to
the demand for computation, and, in particular, trivial requests
are satisfied rapidly.

Input/output facilities are included for saving and
restoring the text of programs, for storing and retrieving
entire working environments in partial stages of
execution, and for reading and writing data in
any of several modes.

Using the data definition facilities,
it is literally possible within an hour
to write programs that perform useful
operations on data such as matrices, complex numbers, vectors, formulas,
rational numbers or polynomials, or on strings, lists or trees.
Defined operations may be associated with unary and binary
operators of the user's own choosing, including redefining the meaning of operators given in the
initial state of the language. 
Data and operator definitions allow the programmer
to assign convenient notations for writing
programs in these and other problem areas.

.sec(Scope,scope)

This document is intended primarily as a reference manual
for PPL, and not as an introductory text
in computer programming.  Although the explanations
attempt to be as complete as possible, they do not
dwell on the simpler or more basic points.
A companion document,
!<An Introduction to PPL Programming>, by T. A. @@<Standish,Thomas A.>,
deals with the basic
concepts of computer programming in a more
detailed and systematic manner, and is recommended
for beginners.  On the other hand,
the !<PPL User's Manual> alone should serve the
needs of those users who have had at least a minimum
of previous experience in computing.

.sec(Organization,organization)

To date, PPL has been implemented on two different computers:
the <<PDP-10> and the <<PDP-11>.  Furthermore, versions of PPL-10
have been implemented to run under both the <<DECsystem-10>
and BBN <<Tenex> operating systems (the PDP-11 version runs
under the <<Unix> operating system).
.see operating system,|DECsystem-10, Tenex, Unix|

Every attempt has been made in the course of PPL development
to maintain complete @@<compatibility,between PPL versions> between all versions of PPL.
The only intentional differences lie in the following areas:

(1) Those due to the different memory word sizes of
the PDP-10 and PDP-11, affecting the limits of magnitude and
precision in numbers; and

(2) Those resulting from differences in operating environments
provided by the respective operating systems, affecting the protocols
used to log in and log out, the control character conventions used
during text typein and editing, and the input/output facilities
available to the programmer.

Except where specifically noted, descriptions in this manual
are applicable to all versions of PPL.  Machine dependencies
will be noted by referring specifically to <<PPL-10> and <<PPL-11>,
and operating system dependencies by referring to the
DECsystem-10, Tenex, and Unix versions of PPL.

This manual reflects version 53 of PPL-10*<At the time
this edition of the manual was prepared, PPL-10 version 53
had not yet been released.  Earlier versions do not contain
the advanced text editing capabilities described in
{"Section" charedit}, but rather contain a somewhat more limited
character-by-character editor described in {"Appendix" apsup10}.>
and version 7 of PPL-11.
Changes made to PPL in later releases will be documented through
revised editions of the manual and through separate update sheets.

.sec(Acknowledgements,ack)

PPL has benefited from the contributions of many individuals.
The language was initially conceived by T.A. @@<Standish,Thomas A.>, at the
National University of Mexico in the summer of 1968.{ref 3}
The design evolved over the next year into the version of PPL
presented at a Working Conference on Extensible Languages
held at Carnegie-Mellon University on 2-4 December 1968 and
at the Extensible Language Symposium held in Boston on
13 May 1969.{ref(|4,5|)}

Implementation of PPL-10 was begun at Harvard in July 1970 by T.A. Standish
and E.A. @@<Taft,Edward A.>, and after proceeding for six months, resulted
in the first working version of PPL.  Major revisions
were undertaken in the summers of 1971 and 1974, during which
time considerable improvements were made in syntax
and program control.

The PDP-11 version of PPL was designed and implemented
at Harvard during 1973-74 by C.J. @@<Prenner,Charles J.> and A.Z. @@<Spector,Alfred Z.>.

